general.description:
Interests:
My primary clinical interests are shoulder joint replacement surgery and instability surgery. 
My current research interests are: shoulder replacement surgery; arthroscopic latarjet reconstructions; rotator cuff repair; & severe frozen shoulder.

Biography:
I undertook a year of postgraduate subspecialty fellowship training at the Princess Alexandra Hospital.
I received the Shoulder and Elbow Society of Australia International Travelling Fellowship.

My private practice is located at the Brisbane Private Hospital.  I believe that it is important to give back to the public hospital system that trained me and to this end I have a public appointment at the Princess Alexandra Hospital, Mater Public Hospital & Cairns Base Hospital. 

I am the chief supervisor of an Australian Orthopaedic Association (AOA) accredited Fellowship in Shoulder Arthroscopy and Arthroplasty, training young Orthopaedic surgeons from overseas and Australia in advanced shoulder arthroscopy and arthroplasty techniques.

I am the Immediate Past President of the Queensland Hand Surgery Society and Secretary of the Queensland Shoulder Society. I am currently the Queensland Chairman of the Australian Society of Orthopaedic Surgeons (ASOS) and Scientific Secretary of the Queensland Branch of the AOA & member of the RACS Regional Committee.  As Scientific Secretary, I am responsible for supervising the teaching programme for the Qld Orthopaedic trainees and convener of annual scientific meeting. 

In 2016 the University of Queensland recognised me for my work when it promoted me to Associate Professor.  I am actively involved in research having published papers in international scientific journals and regularly invited to speak at national and international surgical conferences.

While at Yale, he held the position of Tutor-in-Law for two years, was awarded the Fox International Fellowship to spend a year undertaking research at the University of Cambridge, and visited the University of Copenhagen’s Centre of Excellence for International Courts (iCourts).

His book on the bills of rights in Australia, Canada, New Zealand and the United Kingdom -- From Dialogue to Disagreement in Comparative Rights Constitutionalism (Federation Press, 2016) -- was awarded the Holt Prize in 2015. He has published in a number of Australian, Irish, UK and international journals, including the Dublin University Law Journal, the International Journal of Constitutional Law, the Melbourne University Law Review, and Public Law.

general.headline: General Counsel at Greenpeace Australia Pacific and Finance Presenter at Finance News Network
general.description:
Katrina is the General Counsel for Greenpeace Australia Pacific. She is responsible for implementing and upholding good corporate governance practices; advising the Senior Management Team on a range of legal matters including employment law, contract law and intellectual property; record maintenance and lodgements; assisting in the negotiation and drafting of contracts; leading policy review and conducting compliance assessments. 

Katrina holds a Bachelor of Laws (Honours first class, division one), Bachelor of Business (Distinction) and a Diploma of Legal Practice from the University of Newcastle. She is currently undertaking a PhD in Law focused on transnational business ethics and corporate governance and has presented her research at a number of international conferences, including the 4th Ashridge International Research Conference on Leadership in Berkhamsted, UK, the 5th International Conference on Social Responsibility, Ethics and Sustainable Business in Milan, Italy and the 6th Australian Fraud Summit in Sydney, Australia.

Katrina has previously worked as a commercial lawyer for Clayton Utz. She has been admitted to the Supreme Court of New South Wales and the High Court of Australia and has worked on a number of high profile litigations, regulatory investigations and corporate advisory matters for clients including Woolworths, Idemitsu, the Barangaroo Delivery Authority and the ANZ Bank. 

She is also a fellow of the Centre for Comparative Corporate Governance at Deakin Law School and looks forward to continuing her research on corporate social responsibility, corporate governance, leadership, and transnational business ethics. She is conducting research into these areas in order to provide high quality commercially driven advice to her clients that strikes a balance between economic growth, profitability and good corporate citizenship.
